# TypeScript And Style

- Keep strict typing: avoid `any`; use explicit interfaces/types for reusable domain shapes.
- Narrow `unknown` errors with `instanceof Error` before reading `.message`.
- Prefer small typed helpers in `lib` for reusable transforms instead of repeating inline logic.
- Use existing formatter/lint conventions: single quotes, semicolons, trailing commas, 80-char wrap.
- Prefer stable return types (`T | null`, discriminated unions) over ambiguous implicit `undefined`.

## Example

```ts
// ❌ BAD
function parse(input: any) {
  try {
    return JSON.parse(input);
  } catch (e) {
    throw new Error(e.message);
  }
}

// ✅ GOOD
type ParsedPayload = Record<string, unknown>;

function parse(input: string): ParsedPayload {
  try {
    return JSON.parse(input) as ParsedPayload;
  } catch (error) {
    throw new Error(
      `Failed to parse payload: ${error instanceof Error ? error.message : 'Unknown error'}`
    );
  }
}
```
